The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic already this year.
Maybe
Perhaps the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer almost all services like their partners in Western Europe.
Here, however, something is missing – a virtual operator who has traditional obligations to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be long.
As the Czech operators belong to the most expensive ones in Europe, we have written many times on Mobil.cz.
At the end of the day ČTú also confirmed it, which noted that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the final steps of the European Commission in regulating roaming tariffs, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of mobile blind operators the SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high against Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to start the fight.
Maybe it sounds absurd, too, we have three mobile networks and highly covered over 100 %.
Instead, mobile telephony operators like to boast that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, it also often emphasizes the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTú) , Pavel Dvořák , which in the past has said that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with his own network no longer has many possibilities. (However, it might be difficult to find other frequencies.)
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a significant fall in prices, to which traditional operators would have to react.
At the same time, even before sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, similar voices were echoed in Britain as we do.
However, it has been shown that the place for operators of this kind is there and that they can really succeed.
After all, we must not go too far.
In February of this year we informed you about the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to conquer more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group to which in the Czech Republic belongs among other U:phones.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete group-braining.
In order to actually work, that is, more customers than a traditional operator are needed.
They do not carry behind, i.e., relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
Thus in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer calls and SMS at little price, which is often in balance with the offer of the most restricted services
So for example Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS that cost as little as half as its competitors.
But as shown by the example of Mobilking in Poland it can be a pretty good move even the bet on a group-breed not recently.
This operator aims to say so specifically about men.
"The real men choose Mobilking operator who likes and can be trusted," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can establish a similar concept as in Poland as well.
The press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover from the point of view of services is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic there is no possibility, they say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there will never be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations do not have many expectations.
Mobilking will be switched on in the other countries in our area," he said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman for the Penta financial group.
It therefore indirectly confirmed that current operators in the Czech Republic are not definitely in favour of this thought.
On the contrary, they try to do everything because no competing potential is created.
For some time, it has not hidden its own interest in the launch of a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And first you get better is.
We have repeatedly negotiated on this possibility with all the Czech operators of the mobile network.
We have already been able to progress in negotiations with some of them," says Pavel Kaidl's spokesman.
So maybe better times are coming.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator must have it by the end of the year.
For now, however, there is an impenetrable wall of silence around its creation.
"At this moment we do not believe that in the Czech market there is room for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed to us," he mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň of the Telefónika O2 press section.
The specific nature of the Czech market also applies to other operators.
The T-Mobil Martina Kemrová press spokesman adds in a rare agreement with the O2 declaration: "For now we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue to build".
And he adds: "On the T-Mobile network a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this moment we will have to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it can be considered on the horizon."
Vodafone concentrates its attention rather than reaching its 3G licence requests.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators and this in particular in the context of spending and infrastructure sharing.
We consider this, from the customer's point of view, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet."
Competent authorities - with complicating operators
The attitude of mobile telephone operators can easily be understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thereby to a decrease in profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The disturbances around the creation U:fon testify that when the operators hold to something they know how to get back on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure pressed against ČTú in the period of creation of U:phone to the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to public access information from ČTú web pages.
But right now U:fon serves as a topic for which not to accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová observed: "The competition environment of the mobile telephony market has been greatly enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that another competitor’s entry would place on him and above all on his high claims services.”
However, the attitude of mobile telephony operators is quite surprising to the complete disinterest by the Czech regulators.
It is not only the attitude of the ČTú that unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Britain and other developed countries - has no power to interfere in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, this in relation to the whole problem has taken its typical position.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract of the rental of the required infrastructure between mobile operator and virtual operator had been realized.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers probably has not been quite interesting for traditional operators," said Kristian Chalupa, from the UOHS external relations section, in response to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators might not surprise.
On the other hand, the office which must defend the interests of consumers and, above all, take care of the fact that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, is more than a delicate matter.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Out abroad where virtual operators commonly work, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephony services."
But of course the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of UOHS.
It is truly shocking in the whole situation that the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it really is just a coincidence is a matter for itself.
Similarly, the same price of petrol for all petrol plants is undoubtedly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section has not found any signs of anti-competitive behavior regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so he does not have a corresponding greater responsibility for his behaviour on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing the telecom regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points .
Of course there is the analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTú, according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of economic competition the only market.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator is always necessary the agreement of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has – at the end of the accounts logically – the monopoly of his network.
So for a certain portion must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not accept this argument, for UOHS it should be a minimum alert that three mobile operators do so strangely similar.
At the same time, complaints from stakeholders (including the mentioned GTS Novera company) show that during negotiations with all operators encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to ČTú in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which UOHS is kept out of the whole matter.
This has already been found in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to promote the expansion of Čtú's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved telecommunications law has been updated, despite the fact that many experts from this point of view expected to improve the situation.
This is what UOHS representatives need to know more about, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
You can do it, when no one looks
While we are not aware of the operation of these pseudo-virtual operators, some of them even exist in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own price lists of mobile telephony services but are only partially public.
These are usually multilevel marketing companies.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the ready persons.
The magic is that the company against the operator appears as a classic business customer, which orders a large amount of SIM card.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile telephony operators prohibit a similar presale.
"If the cases in question were presented, of which we will be interested, we could be dealing with breach of contractual conditions, and could result in the conclusion of cooperation with that company," she replied to the question Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile telephone operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
The activities of these companies, that is to say, make a profit that is not indifferent and at the same time - unlike the actual virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way by their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, only a negligible percentage of customers uses the services of these companies.
These must also accept that the SIM card on their phone is not registered on their behalf, so they cannot have in full of it as usual customers of mobile telephone operators "
But this should be a little strange to ČTú.
In addition another issue for UOHS is opened.
If mobile operators close their eyes in front of such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has strong enough rights to hide similar activities and if you do not want to do so you will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When We're Not Costier
As has already been said many times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market has led to a significant fall in prices for services.
At the same time in virtually all countries where operators were born, traditional operators tried to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were almost identical - too small market, at the limit too saturated, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in the developed countries in these cases, the defence regulators intervened not by mobile telephone operators but by their customers.
Both with the formal measures and with the non-formal pressure, then came to the creation of the first virtual operator and to him more.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators launch from one another all the time as a boiling potato.
For our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes it more than comfortable.
But don't throw your sponge.
If the backstage information is right and the virtual operator will really appear from us, the Czech mobile phone market will be re-engineered.
If one of the operators consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only UNOHS could hardly remain impermissible to the refusal (discrimination) of the other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
