The first time it happens, it's at most frightening, but it's not really very important.
This is a benign alteration of sleep called a sleepwalker.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you said that you had spoken in your sleep.
This may occur in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example associated with a high fever episode) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason why this phenomenon can be explained.
Sometimes there are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, night enuresis (do the peep in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As mentioned earlier, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stress situations or overcrowding.
In any case, it is still unstudyed.
Even the intensity with which it appears is extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite occurs (screams, cries, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be appropriate to observe the child and perhaps consult a specialist to check whether there is any question that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a release to the situation.
We have said that it is a benign alteration, therefore, there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if combined with insomnia or stress).
On the other hand, what can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid television programs or series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
