The psychology of auctioning in excess: why spend more money?
Buyers' auctions are willing to spend more, to overestimate the goods.
Neurologists and researchers from the University of New York have been able to discover the neuro-economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study on Science magazine, men do not want to stay back in a race like eBay auction, so they are available to pay even a higher price.
The research tried to trace the nervous scheme of this "participation" at the level of the nervous system through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lot, the other group of players took part in a auction while with the method of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) examined the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games the participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the body strangulated under the cerebral cortex comes into operation intensively when you lose the game.
This brain area, in addition to the other functions, plays a role in the self-gratification mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to researchers, the price rise is explained by scanning the vehement reaction of the strato.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group carried out a financial follow-up survey.
In this investigation three groups have appealed against a partner under different conditions.
The control group reported the actual value of the product in question and made their bet.
Another group besides this promised that in the event of a win they will receive another $15 prize.
The third group would have received $15 before the auction, but the group members would have lost their money in the event of auction loss.
The difference between the two groups consisted of the fact that for one of them the pay has been highlighted, while for the other the loss.
Checking the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the group who played "against the loss" were willing to make higher bets of the control group or "winner".
"These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
In fact, these so far explained the phenomena found in auctions with the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image have helped to resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so that we have come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schutter, professor of the Faculty of Economics of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to speak to your doctor?
Nearly half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, in Hungary instead of the first causes of death, chronic liver diseases are mentioned.
In Hungary, the number of patients with hepatitis amounts to one hundred thousand, of whom only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know how to be infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name of the contagious liver disease caused by several viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical of hepatitis and itteritis, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms according to the pathogen: hepatitis A and E via the food channel (e.g. water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic liquids (sperm, vaginal loss, saliva).
For travellers it is useful to vaccinate against virus A and B, against C there is no vaccine.
Hepatitis A symptoms appear two to three weeks after the consumption of infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellow spots are formed on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the faeces become clear and the dark urine, the healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die every year worldwide for hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is, according to estimates, that only one person in ten receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not cured it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver tumors.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because pathogens subdly destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore it is very important to prevent and perform regular medical tests.
This disease is much more frequent than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattoos.
In the world today, the number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since also a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease, it is worth addressing your family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognised in time the disease is treatable, the virus can be eliminated by the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumours can be prevented.
September 30th is the World Day of Hepatitis, organized for the first time in 2004 worldwide by associations of patients.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and early recognition of the disease.
