The smart car imitates the flight of the skull
What could be the best way to develop anti-collation technologies if you do not imitate the sensors of the obstacles that are in nature?
For example, bees.
In the amazing project presented to CEATEC in Japan, calabrons gave the initial strategic direction to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collation systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built the BR23C biomimetic robot, a robotic mini car provided with bee properties, with the ultimate purpose of creating a system capable of scanning all collisions.
Flying bees form their own oval personal space that really resembles our protective shield - explained to the Kazuhiro Two exhibition, director of PR technology and research and development.
Important is the role of the ape view, capable of a visual of 300 degrees in each direction.
Engineers have attracted the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the ape view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within 180 degrees radius, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the ape, changes direction immediately turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, unlike the current system, takes place completely instinctively.
"If it weren't so, the robot auto wouldn't react quickly to avoid collisions," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the auto robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the harmful and internal layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in an eyebeat.
But unlike bees, deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of wheel slenderness.
In this way, instead of the endless possibilities available to bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as available possibility, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lithium polymer batteries, lighter and with a high energy density, which means that their duration is greater than that of lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the existence of intelligent reaction is important, not data processing or even less the ability to store it.
This robot has to process some input in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so use only a memory of a few tens of Kb.
There's no need for a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions which, according to Nissan, can be installed on serial vehicles within 10 years.
Further possibilities of application can be represented by unification with GPS satellite navigation system that avoids obstacles on the road leads to destination.
