To disappear are often historical places and memory loads," it's as if there's less a friend, a acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of road and many emotions," says the director of New Cinema Paradiso, the film that 20 years ago added to Tornatore the Oscar Prize and the Grand Prix of Cannes Jury, and which told the poetry of a province hall and nostalgia for a way to live the lost cinema perhaps forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of the exhibitors, speak clear: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and to pay for the major scotto are mainly the salts in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 single-sala movies, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to demonstrate that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multisala cinemas: 195 extra screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 both in Tuscany and in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed unreasonably" notes Paolo Protti, President of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures but it would have to ensure the survival of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its hosts are willing to move into the multiplex.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund in favour of operators: the government's prior debt is around 10 million euros.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the Government does not comply with existing laws.
In order to support the sector, it would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year".
Interesting the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, concerned about the closures, has decided to run to the shelters with the signature of a protocol between the Town and Anec, the first of this type in Italy, to protect and promote the cinemas monosala both in the historical center and in the periphery.
Among the rules laid down are tax relief measures in favour of managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: spectators can enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for stopping and parking.
"It's an initiative I like" observes Giuseppe Tornatore, and I hope other cities follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
It is true, however, that in order to contrast the ripple of the multiplex the traditional salts must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradise", to which I had been thinking for 10 years.
